### Configure Payload CMS with Block References for Performance

Source: https://github.com/payloadcms/payload/blob/main/docs/fields/blocks.mdx

This configuration demonstrates how to define a Payload CMS block once globally and then reference it by its slug in collection fields and rich text editors. This approach optimizes performance by avoiding redundant block definitions, reducing client-side data, and ensuring blocks are immutable when referenced. It requires listing the block slug in `blockReferences` and keeping the `blocks` array empty for compatibility, noting that referenced blocks cannot be modified per collection and have isolated access control.

```typescript
import { buildConfig } from 'payload'
import { lexicalEditor, BlocksFeature } from '@payloadcms/richtext-lexical'

// Payload Config
const config = buildConfig({
  // Define the block once
  blocks: [
    {
      slug: 'TextBlock',
      fields: [
        {
          name: 'text',
          type: 'text',
        },
      ],
    },
  ],
  collections: [
    {
      slug: 'collection1',
      fields: [
        {
          name: 'content',
          type: 'blocks',
          // Reference the block by slug
          blockReferences: ['TextBlock'],
          blocks: [], // Required to be empty, for compatibility reasons
        },
      ],
    },
    {
      slug: 'collection2',
      fields: [
        {
          name: 'editor',
          type: 'richText',
          editor: lexicalEditor({
            features: [
              BlocksFeature({
                // Same reference can be reused anywhere, even in the lexical editor, without incurred performance hit
                blocks: ['TextBlock'],
              }),
            ],
          }),
        },
      ],
    },
  ],
})
```

